Duck Typing is a programming concept that originated in Python. It is a way of checking whether an object has a certain property or method, regardless of its type. In other words, if an object behaves like a duck (meets the requirements), then it is considered a duck, regardless of its actual type. This means that in Duck Typing, the type of an object is less important than how it behaves.

In TypeScript, you can use Duck Typing to check the properties or methods of an object without having to worry about its type. This can make your code more flexible and easier to read, as you can focus on the behavior of the object rather than its type. For example, you can write a function that takes an object as an argument and checks if it has a certain property or method, like this:

function myFunction(obj) {
  if (obj.hasProperty("myProp")) {
    // Do something
  } else {
    // Handle the case where the object doesn't have the property
  }
}

In this example, the function takes an object as an argument and checks if it has a property called "myProp". If the object has this property, the function can use it. If the object doesn't have the property, the function can handle the case in a different way.

In this way, TypeScript and Duck Typing can be used together to write more flexible and readable code. Type annotations can help catch errors early on, while Duck Typing allows you to focus on the behavior of objects and write more flexible code.

